@node Intro "Introduction"
@{u}Introduction@{uu}

This script is a modified and improved version of a script written by Les Hellawell.

I wrote this script to help troubleshooting when a program requests a 
library with a certain version. This script will make a list of all 
the libraries in libs:, filtering all files that are not libraries. 
It also filters out the following libraries as they may crash the 
system:
 
	@{b}mathieeedoubbas.library@{ub}
	@{b}mathieeedoubtrans.library@{ub}
	@{b}mathieeesingtrams.library@{ub}
	@{b}mathtrans.library@{ub}

The script will then find the version number of all other libraries, 
and output the result to a file in ram, which can be printed out for 
future reference. The date is also written to the file, which is 
handy if you need to update the list. 

I am not an arexx expert, but this script does what I need it to do. 
I would appreciate any comments, feedback or suggestions about these scripts. 
Please contact @{"me" link author} if you do.  

@endnode
@node req "Requirements"
@{u}Requirements@{uu}

Here is a list of the requirements needed to run this scripts:

-Rexxmast running in the background.
-Harddrive is essential :-), this script could take a LONG time processing all 
 libraries on a floppy.
-version command in c:
-Newicons for the included icon.

See the @{"Usage" link use} section for using this script. 
@endnode

@node use "Usage"
@{u}Usage@{uu}

@{b}The Easy way@{ub}
Double click on the provided icon and off she goes@{i}!@{ui}! 
Then load the file liblist (in RAM:) with multiview, you can print this for future reference.

@{b}The Hard way@{ub}
Open up a shell. If Rexxmast is not already running, run it now by typing Rexxmast.

If the script is in your path, then type, without the quotes:
 @{b}"rx liblister"@{ub}

Results and the status of the script will be displayed in the shell 
window. When the script is finished, a text file with all libraries 
and their version numbers will be created in ram:, it will be named 
liblist. You can print this file from multiview or a text editor if 
you want. 
 
@endnode
